:{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83509"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 65-year-old man presents with a one week history of passing blood in his urine. There is no pain on urination, but he is getting up at night to void and his stream is not as strong as it used to be. He is not on any medication and has a 40 pack-year smoking history. He works as a hairdresser and drinks about two cans of beer every evening.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Voided urine cytology","Cystoscopy +/- biopsy","Urine dipstick test","PSA (prostate-specific antigen)","MRI abdomen and pelvis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe prime concern is whether or not the underlying cause of this patient\u0027s haematuria is a malignancy within the urinary tract. Thus he will need the upper tract imaged (CT urogram in preference to MRI) and the lower tract inspected (\u003Cstrong\u003Eflexible cystoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E). Whilst he certainly has risk factors bladder cancer, this diagnosis cannot be assumed. His known risk factors being his exposure to dyes (in his work as a hair dresser) and his smoking history (the biggest risk factor for bladder cancer). Other risk factors include age \u0026gt;70, male gender, family history + pioglitazone (medication used for type 2 diabetes).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA common presentation for bladder cancer is painless macroscopic haematuria. Therefore, this patient requires thorough investigation for bladder cancer. Cystoscopy is the key diagnostic investigation for bladder cancer. This procedure can be performed simply via flexible cystoscopy without anaesthesia and provides a tissue diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA urine dipstick is important to rule out infection, but considering his risk of bladder cancer it is not the most important investigation. PSA is used more in prostate cancer and CT urogram in kidney stones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bladder cancer can present as painless haematuria","The investigation of choice for suspected bladder cancer is a cystoscopy with biopsy"],"references":["Cancer.Net Editorial Board. Bladder Cancer: Diagnosis [Internet]. American Society of Clinical Oncology; 2019. Available from: https://www.cancer.net/cancer-types/bladder-cancer/diagnosis.","Sun M, Trinh QD. Diagnosis and staging of bladder cancer. Hematol Oncol Clin North Am. 2015 Apr;29(2):205-18, vii. doi: 10.1016/j.hoc.2014.10.013. Epub 2014 Nov 6. PMID: 25836929. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25836929/","DeGeorge KC, Holt HR, Hodges SC. Bladder Cancer: Diagnosis and Treatment. Am Fam Physician. 2017 Oct 15;96(8):507-514. PMID: 29094888. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29094888/","Guldhammer CS, V\u00e1squez JL, Kristensen VM, Norus T, Nadler N, Jensen JB, Azawi N. Cystoscopy Accuracy in Detecting Bladder Tumors: A Prospective Video-Confirmed Study. Cancers (Basel). 2023 Dec 28;16(1):160. doi: 10.3390/cancers16010160. PMID: 38201586; PMCID: PMC10777997. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38201586/","Khan J, Kamal MS, D\u0027Arcy FT, Dowling C. Biopsy at flexible cystoscopy: is it worthwhile? Ir J Med Sci. 2021 Feb;190(1):437-439. doi: 10.1007/s11845-020-02284-6. Epub 2020 Jul 1. PMID: 32613562. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32613562/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68382"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"343"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68382"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-04T20:53:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-04T20:54:34+10:30